Subject: (19US-Full) ELECTRONICS LAB II (004) (2195-1_20EECE3071L004): Lab report format
Body:
This is the lab report format

*	Cover Page: Title, authors, date of complete lab
*	Objective: This may be copied from the lab assignment document or you may write one in your own words
*	Principles of Operation: Description (in your own words) as to the function of the circuit and comparisons to other circuit topologies (as necessary). Generally show that you understand how the circuit operates (e.g. Why does a common emitter amplifier have an out-of-phase output (w.r.t. the input)?)
*	Theory: Derivations of equations (labeled) to be used in calculating the various relevant parameters of the circuit. Please do not simply list the equations without explanation for how they came to be. Also include any relevant DC/AC models of the circuit.
*	Design and Simulation: Calculations using equations from the Theory section, simulations of DC biasing and frequency response of the circuit (Bode plot)
*	Test Results: Your actual measured values and experimentally determined Bode plot, corner frequencies, bandwidth, etc.
*	Analysis: Description of your results, comparison between calculated, simulated, and measured values (i.e. relative error, etc.), and possible explanations for any discrepancies. Also, do not simply state that an error could have occurred for a given reason, explain how that reason would have affected the result (e.g. explaining in what way a shift in capacitance would affect the corner frequency vs. just stating that capacitance could have changed the value)
*	Conclusion: A short concluding paragraph summarizing your lab experience, what you learned, and how you will apply that learning in the future

If you have any additional questions, please do not hesitate to ask.

Subject: Code
Body:
clear;

clc;

close all;

 

%create signals

x1 = inline('(t+10)*(t>=-10&t<=-5)+(-t+10)*(t>=5&t<=10)');           

x2 = inline('5*(t>=-5&t<=-5)+5*(t>=5&t<=5)');      

 

timevec = -15:1:15;                %time interval of signals           

length_timevec = length(timevec);

tau = -15:1:15;                   %shifting interval

length_tau = length(tau);

x1t = zeros(1,length_timevec);      %arrays to be filled later

x2t = zeros(1,length_timevec);

y = zeros(1,length_timevec);

conv = zeros(1,length_tau);

dt = 0;                             %used for indexing in for loops

 

for i = timevec

    dt = dt+1;

    x1t(dt) = x1(i);        %array of timevec values of t for x1

    x2t(dt) = x2(i);        %array of timevec values of t for x2

end

dt = 0;             

for i = timevec

    dt = dt+1;              

    dtau = 0;               %used for indexing convolution

   for j = tau

       dtau = dtau+1;

       conv(1,dtau) = x1(i-j).*x2(j);   %convolving x1 and x2 

   end

   y(1,dt) = sum(conv);          %summing the convolution array to obtain y(t) for the specific t

end

%plotting figures

figure(1)

subplot(3,1,1)

stem(timevec,x1t);      %x1(t)

title('x1(t)')

xlabel('t')

ylabel('x1(t)')

subplot(3,1,2)

stem(timevec,x2t);      %x2(t)

title('x2(t)')

xlabel('t')

ylabel('x2(t)')

subplot(3,1,3)

stem(timevec,y);        %y(t)

title('Convolution of x1(t) and x2(t)')

xlabel('t')

ylabel('y(t) = \int x2(\tau)x1(t-\tau)d\tau')

 

Sent from Mail <https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkId=550986>  for Windows 10

Enjoy the homecoming weekend!

-Brian

Subject: 2188-1_20EECE2070L002 ((18FS-Full) ELECTRONICS LAB I (002)): Graded Lab 2 Brief and Grades Posted on BB - Deadline for Lab 3 Report Submission Extended
Body:
I finished grading your lab 2 briefs just now and have posted your grades along with PDF files annotated with my comments on the BB. 

There were many mistakes in the lab briefs that I tried to ignore and not take off any points. However, I added my comments so you can avoid them in the upcoming reports. As we move forward, we expect the quality of reports to go up, so reoccurring mistakes will have a larger impact on the grades. 

Many mistakes could have been avoided if you read through the recent report template I posted on Blackboard (link below). There have also been new threads of questions and answers in the "Discussion Board" on BB that you can use in case you have similar questions. 

Lastly, I am going to extend the deadline for submission of lab 3  reports to Wednesday midnight so you would have enough time for making changes on your lab 3 report based on the feedback from graded lab 2 briefs. 

See you in class tomorrow,

Ashkan

Ashkan, 




On the lab one quiz, question 5, we are asked to figure out what voltage the multimeter is measuring, and the 'correct' answer is that it is measuring 'V-b'. However, point B is just a single point on a wire. I am not sure how the multimeter could be measuring the voltage at a single point when it is connected across multiple resistors. All of the other answers were measuring the voltage across multiple points such as 'V-ab' or 'V-bc'. Am I just misunderstanding the meaning of 'V-b'? If so, what is the meaning of this label?




Thank you,

Brayden Osborne

Subject: 2188-1_20EECE2070L002 ((18FS-Full) ELECTRONICS LAB I (002)): No Lab Next Wednesday and More Details
Body:
Hello All,

This may be the longest email I send out in the entire semester, but please read it carefully as it contains important information that we will follow for the entire semester:

*	The link for submitting Lab 1 brief is available (two attempts allowed). It is due the end of Tuesday, Sept 4. After that, the link will not be available. I will finish grading the briefs on Wednesday, Sept 12, so you'd be able to go through it and avoid similar mistakes in upcoming reports.
*	The lab brief template is posted on blackboard  ( /Course Documents/Templates and Data Sheets/Templates/Lab Brief Template ).  The submitted file should be a Single PDF containing the following items:

	1.	Page 1 is the page 1 of the template (your name, class day, etc.)
	2.	Page 2 is the page 2 of the template containing the lab objective (Write in your own words. DO NOT USE the same objective given to you on the lab write-ups).
	3.	Page 3 will be the scan of the completed lab write-up handed to you in class. Each  group member should also include a scanned copy of their calculations on a separate sheet (one sheet of calculations per group member). 
	4.	After page 3, you will have your simulation results (typically 2-5 pages). 
	5.	Next comes each team member's analysis (typically 2-4 pages) and conclusion (typically 1 to 3 pages)

*	Items 1-4 are shared sections (except the calculations sheet in item 3 which is one sheet per person). Item 5 (Analysis and Conclusion) is NOT a shared section meaning that each person writes his own analysis and conclusion and appends it to the end of the PDF file to be submitted.
*	There are many details that you need to pay attention to when writing a technical report after you get a job. Hence, we practice writing a quality report in this class. Make sure you read the file "E1 Lab Brief Format.pdf" posted on BB ( /Course Documents/Templates and Data Sheets/Templates/Lab Brief Format )  for a review of these details and accompanied examples.  
*	The sheet of calculations mentioned in item 3 of the lab brief template above is essentially your lab pre-work which starting from next lab, you will submit in a separate link before the class (due one hour before the class and done on an Engineering paper)
*	I have made discussion forums on the BB ( /Tools/Discussion Board ) to discuss questions related to lab brief/report and pre-work. Students who show good activity in the forums can claim extra credit added to their final grade.

One last important note, There will be no class on next Wednesday, Sept 5th. That is  because the Monday class is off, and I'd like to keep the Wednesday class on the same schedule as the Monday section.   
Let me know if any question.  
Have a nice weekend, 
Ashkan
